154:   e. **Idempotency check (spec DB 8).** The retry line to write is `retry <count+1>/3: <reason> at <ts>` where `<ts> = g.currentDateTime.Now().UTC().Format(time.RFC3339)`. Before writing, read the on-disk body and check whether a `## Progress` line for THIS attempt number already exists: scan the on-disk body for any line whose `strings.TrimSpace` starts with the literal prefix `retry <count+1>/3:` (attempt number match; the reason/timestamp suffix is ignored for the idempotency key). If such a line already exists AND `existingFrontmatter`'s `planning_retry_count` already equals `count` (the value we just read) — meaning a prior processing already bumped the counter and appended this line — treat as a redelivery: log `glog.V(2).Infof("planning-retry: attempt %d already recorded for %s; idempotent no-op", count+1, req.TaskIdentifier)`, do NOT increment the metric, do NOT write, and return `(true, nil)` (handled — suppress the default write so redelivery does not re-run `WriteResult` either). NOTE the subtlety: the counter is bumped in the SAME atomic write that appends the line, so on redelivery the on-disk counter reflects the bump. Read carefully: the incoming `req` has the pre-bump snapshot, but `existingFrontmatter` (on-disk) has the post-bump value. Therefore the correct idempotency detection is: read `onDiskCount` from `existingFrontmatter`; the "next attempt" would be `onDiskCount+1`; if the on-disk body already contains a `retry <onDiskCount>/3:` line (i.e. the line for the attempt that produced the current on-disk count), the retry for that attempt already happened — but the arriving failed result is for the OLD attempt. Implement the check as: if the on-disk body already contains a line with prefix `retry <onDiskCount>/3:` for `onDiskCount >= 1`, the most recent retry write already landed; if additionally the on-disk `phase` is already `planning` and the on-disk `task_identifier` differs from `req.TaskIdentifier`'s embedded id semantics is not reliable — so use the simpler, robust rule: **maintain a per-attempt marker.** Write the retry line as `retry <count+1>/3: <reason> at <ts>`. On redelivery the on-disk count is `count+1`, so recomputing "next attempt" yields `count+2`; the code will look for a `retry <count+2>/3:` line, not find it, and would wrongly retry again. To prevent this, gate the retry on the counter transition itself: only perform the write inside the `AtomicReadModifyWriteAndCommitPush` modify closure where you RE-READ the current on-disk frontmatter; if the re-read counter is already `> count` (someone bumped it since `FindTaskFilePath`), return the current bytes unchanged (no-op write) and signal via a captured bool that no increment happened. Concretely: implement the idempotency inside the modify closure (step f) which re-reads under the git lock, and use `count` (the value read in step c) as the expected pre-bump value; if the modify closure sees `onDiskCount != count`, it returns `current` unchanged. This is the authoritative, race-free idempotency mechanism. The metric increment (step g) must therefore be conditioned on the modify closure having actually bumped the counter — capture that in a closure-scoped `*bool`.
